observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE require the GAD Focal Person to

(a)strictly observe   the provisions under JMC No. 2013-01 as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 which provides for the Guidelines on the Localization of the Magna Carta of Women;  

(b) ensure the early preparation and submission of the GPB to DILG for review/approval and thereafter, for endorsement to  PCW; 

(c) establish and submit to the Audit Team the details of accomplishment report together with their supporting documents to validate the expenses charged to the GAD fund;

(d) monitor the GAD accomplishments based on the approved GPB and submit to DILG on a timely basis;

(e) set up and maintain the GAD database which will serve as the basis for planning, formulation of policies and identification of GAD responsive projects, programs and activities; and  

(f) recommend the formulation of a GAD Code to support the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s rights, women’s economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment.

We recommended that the LCE require the 

(a) Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to 

(i) closely coordinate with the LBP for the immediate notification of downloaded funds by the bank to the Municipal Officials; 

(ii) immediately inform the respective DBM officials of the Municipality’s Land Bank of the Philippines – Trust Fund (LBP TF) account number for future downloading of funds intended for specific projects; 

(b)  Municipal Engineer to take the initiative to inform the concerned Procurement Unit and the Bids and Awards Committee on the timetable of project procurement and implementation and provide the list of projects with corresponding funding sources; 

(c) Municipal DRRMO to plan and monitor the progress of accomplishment of the projects; and  

(d) Municipal Administrator to 

(i) assign an official in charge of projects funded by external sources for strict monitoring of implementation schedules and targets; 

(ii) ensure that the fund proponent is informed on the project status including the liquidation reports and related documents; 

(iii) see to it that, henceforth, all LGSF projects will be completed at the earliest possible time.

We recommended that the LCE require the GAD Focal Person to: 

(i)  ensure the early preparation and submission of the GPB to DILG for review/approval and thereafter for endorsement to PCW; 

(ii)  set up and maintain the GAD database which will serve as the basis for planning, formulation of policies and identification of GAD responsive projects, programs and activities and strict observance of the provisions under JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01;  

(iii) recommend the formulation of a GAD Code to support the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s rights, women’s economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment; and 

(iv) monitor the GAD accomplishments based on the approved GPB and submit accordingly to the DILG on a timely basis.

We recommended that the LCE require the head of the MENRO to 
(a) closely monitor the establishment of MRF in the barangays to fully comply with the law; 

(b) strictly implement the segregation of wastes at source and impose appropriate sanctions; 

(c) include in the budget the provision for adequate, effective and comfortable personal protective equipment to garbage collectors and MRF workers to protect them from the hazards of handling wastes; 

(d) evaluate the working conditions of workers at the MRF and at the field and provide them protection from occupational work hazards while in transit; and 

(e) provide the waste compartment of all garbage trucks with adequate cover to ensure the containment of the solid wastes while in transit to prevent spillage.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor 

(a) consider constructing a central storage area/ stockroom to house all deliveries of supplies; 

(b) require the property/ supply custodians to 

(i)	make use of RIS for every withdrawal/issuance of supplies and submit to Accounting Office the MRSI;

(ii)	submit the inventory report on supplies every semester while the Property and Equipment inventory count report at year-end on or before January 31 of the following year; and 

(iii)	maintain stock cards/subsidiary records for individual items on stock.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the head of MENRO to 

(a) strictly implement wastes segregation at source; 

(b) consider the application of appropriate sanctions if sorting by household is not done; 

(c) closely monitor the solid waste practices of barangays without MRF; and 

(d) limit the expenditures for hauling by setting a certain quota or limit of truckload per day for each barangay depending on the existing population and livelihood.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the

(a) GAD Focal Person to: 

(i)	strictly observe the scheduled GAD Planning and Budgeting as provided by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2013-01, and its amendments under JMC No. 2016-01 which provides for the Guidelines on the Localization of the Magna Carta of Women to facilitate timely submission; 

(ii)	establish GAD database to serve as the basis for planning, formulating policies and identifying GAD responsive projects, programs and activities; 

(iii)	submit the details of expenses charged to GAD fund for validation purposes; and 

(b) assign personnel to monitor the required schedule in the submission of the GAD Plan and Budget to DILG for review and approval and on the submission of GPB and AR to COA under item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor 

(a) require the MSWDO to 

(i)	conduct regular validation of SCs to be used as a database in the grant of Social Pension to qualified and eligible SCs such as the indigent SCs, Persons with disability and sick with incurable illness; 

(ii)	consider inclusion of thumbmarks of SCs and SC’s data on siblings on the application form for membership; 

(iii)	coordinate with NPO to come up with the database of the qualified/priority indigent SC beneficiaries; and 

(iv)	validate the list of SCs eligible for the Social Pension Program before submission to DSWDO to determine the present health condition of SCs if needing replacement so other SCs can benefit from the Program and available funds could be fully utilized.

We recommended that Management require the: 

a) BUB Focal Person to strictly oversee the timely implementation of all planned programs and projects;    


b) BAC officials to ensure that the voucher for payment is supported with the original copies of the required documents;  

c) Municipal Engineer to submit the original technical documents mentioned above; and 

d) Municipal Accountant to return to the Bureau of Treasury the long outstanding balance of the Due to NGAS account with completed projects/programs and to the source agencies the unspent fund balances of BUB projects with identified government agencies.

We recommended that Management require the 

a) Municipal Human Relations Officer to inform all GSIS members of the Municipality to secure and submit the GSIS ID number; 

b) Municipal Accountant to verify and make the necessary adjustments to those accounts with over or under deduction or remittance.

(a) strictly observe the guidelines in the granting and utilization of the Confidential Fund in accordance with Joint Circular No. 1 dated January 8, 2015; 

(b) submit the cash advance vouchers to the audit team together with the supporting documents in the manner prescribed by the Joint Circular; and 
(c) submit to Office of the COA Chairperson thru the ICFAU, the liquidation reports covering expenses for intelligence fund for CY 2016 for post audit and evaluation thereof.

(a) instruct the Solid Waste Management Board to cause the speedy preparation of the City Solid Waste  Management Plan and its supporting documents as their basis in the effective implementation of solid waste management; 

(b) provide necessary support in the establishment of MRFs at the Barangays; 

(c) cause an efficient and safe operation in the barangay MRFs through proper segregation of wastes and in the Municipality’s dumping station through provision of a fence to prevent hazards to the environment; 

d) encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes; and 

(e) recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003.

We recommended that  Management instruct 

the GSO to properly maintain property cards and take the lead in the Inventory Committee in conducting annually physical inventory count for all items of PPE and immediately submit the physical inventory report to the Accounting Office for reconciliation purposes;

(b) the Accounting Office to update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards being maintained by their office;

(c)  the Inventory Committee to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor in tracing the whereabouts of the Certificates of Title for lots owned by the Municipality; and 

(d) the GSO to submit the necessary documents attendant to their request for disposal with a view to disposing the same in the soonest possible time to prevent further deterioration of the value thereof.

We recommended that Management 

(a) maintain special accounts for each economic enterprise in the General Fund; 


(b) operate and manage the corporate economic enterprises separate and distinct from purely government/public functions;

(c) segregate the assets, liabilities and equity of the economic enterprises from the General Fund proper; 

(d) manage these assets to derive profits as additional source of revenues; 

(e) identify and maintain appropriate property subsidiary ledger cards; and 

(f) prepare the financial reports for each of the economic enterprise.

We recommended that Management 

(a) impose all available legal remedies under RA 7160 to compel delinquent market stall tenants to settle their unpaid accounts; 

(b) regularly send demand letters and notice of delinquency to the stallholders concerned; 

(c) adopt a collection strategy whereby the stallholders would be encouraged to settle their accounts; and 

(d) instruct the members of the Market Committee to regularly hold meeting together with the stall holders to discuss problems affecting their leased stalls and other matters pertaining to market operations.
